description: From Middle English destine et al., from Old French destinee, from Latin dēstinō (English destine). Displaced native Old English wyrd.

entries.meaning: That to which any person or thing is destined; a predetermined state; a condition predestined by the Divine or by human will.
examples: Death is the destiny of all mortal men.

entries.meaning: That which is inevitable in the fullness of time.
One's eventual fate (not necessarily inevitable or predestined).
The fixed order of things; invincible necessity; an irresistible power or agency conceived of as determining the future, whether in general or of an individual.
examples: Dara doesn't believe in using dating apps - she insists that destiny will find her other half.
